## ☸️ Task 3: Kubernetes — Three Namespaces

```yaml
# k8s/base/namespaces.yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Namespace
metadata:
  name: iot-app
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Namespace
metadata:
  name: iot-broker
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Namespace
metadata:
  name: iot-infra
```

### What goes where:

| Namespace | Components | Workload Types |
|-----------|-----------|----------------|
| `iot-app` | IoT backend (2 replicas), Web app (2 replicas) | Deployments |
| `iot-broker` | Broker gateway (2r), Telemetry worker (3r), TTL cleanup (hourly) | StatefulSet, Deployment, CronJob |
| `iot-infra` | Kafka (3r), PostgreSQL (1r), InfluxDB (1r), MongoDB (1r) | StatefulSets with PVCs |

---

## 📡 Task 4: Kafka Topics Configuration

| Topic | Partitions | Retention | Purpose |
|-------|-----------|-----------|---------|
| `iot.telemetry` | 6 | 7 days | Sensor data from devices |
| `iot.commands` | 3 | 1 day | Commands to devices |
| `iot.device-events` | 3 | 3 days | Device status changes (online/offline) |
| `iot.cmd-responses` | 3 | 1 day | Command acknowledgments from devices |

> [!NOTE]
> All messages are keyed by `{group_id}:{device_id}`. Kafka hashes the key to partition, guaranteeing per-device ordering. With 6 partitions on `iot.telemetry`, you can run up to 6 telemetry worker replicas.

Use Strimzi `KafkaTopic` resources or create manually:
```bash
kafka-topics.sh --create --topic iot.telemetry --partitions 6 --replication-factor 3 \
  --config retention.ms=604800000 --bootstrap-server kafka:9092
```

